  "grammarPoint": {
    "title": "Accusative for people: animate masculine nouns change too",
    "explanation": "Yesterday, masculine *things* stayed the same in the accusative (телеви́зор → телеви́зор). But masculine nouns for **people** work differently: they take **-а** (or **-я** after a soft consonant), same as the genitive. **брат → бра́та**, **друг → дру́га**: **Я ви́жу бра́та** — I see my brother.\n\nFeminine nouns keep the same -а→-у rule regardless of person or thing: **сестра́ → сестру́**.",
    "examples": [
      { "ru": "Я ви́жу бра́та.", "en": "I see (my) brother.", "note": "animate masc. → -а" },
      { "ru": "Я встреча́ю сестру́.", "en": "I'm meeting (my) sister.", "note": "fem. -а → -у, same as things" },
      { "ru": "Я покупа́ю хлеб.", "en": "I'm buying bread.", "note": "inanimate masc., unchanged" },
      { "ru": "Я ем я́блоко.", "en": "I'm eating an apple.", "note": "neuter, unchanged" }
    ]
  },

